Barack Obama receives the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth president of the United States
U.S. President Barack Obama arrives in Oslo, Norway, for 26 hours to receive the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth U.S. president in history.
In addition, he is awarded the diploma as well as the medal and a check over $1.4 million for his extraordinary efforts to intensify world diplomacy and cooperation among peoples.
The White House chief arrives tomorrow with his wife Michelle in the northern metropolis and will be busy all the time.
First, he pays a visit to the Nobel Institute, where he meets for the first time with the five committee members who elected him in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The couple then planned to meet with King Harald V of Norway and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit reaches its peak with the ceremony in which Obama takes over the prestigious award.
He is the fourth president of the United States, but only the third to receive the award directly in office.
The White House has already warned that Obama will talk about the war in Afghanistan when he takes over the prize.
The president does not want to avoid this issue because he knows that he will take the prize as a president who is currently waging war in two countries.
He stepped up the war effort a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forget to highlight.
At the ceremony, Obama also received the Golmedaille, the diploma and the cheque for ten million Swedish kronor (about 24 million Czech kronor).
He intends to donate the money for charitable purposes, but has not yet decided on a concrete charitable work.
The event program will then include a banquet with the President and his wife, in which, in addition to the King and Queen of Norway, the Prime Minister and 250 other invited guests will be present.
Obama was very cautious about the price right from the start.
He said, for example, that he felt that he did not fully deserve the award.
He also repeated several times that the price is not just for him, but for all those who aspire to the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he stated that for him this is an "invitation to action".
