USA: Repetition is Mother of Wisdom
It is almost comical with what student zeal Barack Obama, the president with his reputation as the smartest, repeats his predecessor’s strategy in the Afghanistan question, which he himself considered to be the dumbest.
When he finally decimated his long-awaited Afghanistan doctrine, it turned out that he wrote it off over the copy paper from the Bush-Iraq scenario three years ago.
Not only did he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, he even used the name of the Bush declaration of January 2007 as the name of his own declaration: "New Way Forward" without procrastinating.
Three years ago, he himself criticized the Bush idea of sending fresh troop contingents into Iraq, which was plagued by the civil war, as an "irresponsible and, consequently, a catastrophic decision".
The following months, however, showed that the Bush strategy based on military recommendations was the only possible and very successful one, so much so that today the news about Iraq is no longer talked about at all.
Bush’s reputation was not improved by this, because objectively he left his successor a much more grateful starting situation than expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will happen again.
He was again asked by the military to increase his troop strength, especially by the commander-in-chief of the Afghanistan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who, even in spite of his subordination habits, harshly criticized the poignant shooters in the White House.
He called for 40,000 soldiers to be able to reverse the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but did not come up with a better idea and so he cheated the general by 10,000 soldiers.
From Europe, he pressed the pledge for another 5,000, even if he himself originally expected at least 10,000.
His plan to withdraw troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and to complete this process within three years is highly problematic for the entire Obama strategy. The whole Obama doctrine leaves more questions than answers.
Some doubt that the halved increase will have the same effect as the measure in Iraq.
Despite the brotherly war of recent years, the Iraqi society is relatively well structured, its leaders honor the values.
The Afghan situation is marked by the contraindication - no one can be trusted and no agreements are made.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, which are used to changing their minds every day.
The political institutions, even if formally founded correctly, remain only sham structures, behind which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to grow.
The balancing of interests between the various ethnic groups is unusually complicated, especially because of the incomprehensibility of the conditions that further complicate the Pakistan and Iran influences.
The establishment of a “capable state” which is the minimalist goal of the whole operation is also very unrealistic.
Time horizon of Obama strategy alienated by his voluntarism
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened further and is now on the verge of explosion.
Believing that the little soldiers who broke into the war cry about the "early return" can create a miracle here, only a truly romantic soul, which cannot be impressed by facts.
From a political point of view, the timing of the troop withdrawal is purely irresponsible, because the Taliban will accept this as the indirect confession of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in the fighting in Afghanistan is declining.
Europe’s politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is related to the war in the Hindu Kush mountains.
Another possible factor that can radically affect the situation is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions on the Iranians do not work, a very serious question arises for the United States whether the problem can not be solved with troops.
This question needs to be answered in the period in which America is moving toward Obama’s withdrawal from Afghanistan.
But any solution will also mean a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
The only consolation for Barack Obama is the fact that three years remain until the presidential election, and thus there is still enough time for him to resort to a different strategy if it turns out to be a total failure.
