The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, from the VSCHT (Chemical-Technological University) Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens the way to dealing with virus resistance.
They have shown that the substances called metallocarborane act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
The metallocarboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the virus proliferation in a different way than all the drugs used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists arrive at new "improved" compounds, which were prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus protein.
The metal carboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-layered cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Insidious and persistent virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus cleavage caused by the HIV protease, no mature infectious virus particles would be produced.
When we turn off the HIV protease, we also turn off the multiplication of the virus in the patient’s body, the scientists explain in the press report published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the paper, which was published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe entire series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically further modified.
Slightly weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against the HIV protease was tested in the test tube, also against their persistent (resistant) variants, which were obtained from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of the metallocarborane on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as that of the clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect on the resistant variants, against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action, as well as its other properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical designs, makes the metallocarboranes interesting compounds for further research aimed at the development of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlina Rezacova, head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology of the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology of the Institute of Organic Chemistry of the Academy of Chemistry.
