New Vaccination
Vaccinations free for August children
Starting in January, children can be vaccinated against pneumococcal disease free of charge, who were born on August 2 last year and later.
The condition is that they have not yet received a vaccine dose.
Those who have already started vaccination in the last year or earlier will also have to pay for further revaccination themselves.
The first dose should be given between the 3rd and 5th month of the child's life.
Last year, a quarter of families had their children vaccinated against pneumococcal disease.
The parents paid 1,600 crowns and more for one dose.
For the vaccination of the youngest children, four doses are required.
Overall, experts estimate that the health insurance for the vaccine doses spend 300,000 to 450,000 crowns per year.
However, they save on the treatment that children would need without vaccination.
So far, the state has spent about 500,000 per year on all of the children’s area vaccinations.
The mandatory vaccination was introduced with the so-called Janota package.
Pneumococci cause middle ear inflammation, but also serious infections including brain skin inflammation and blood poisoning.
Pneumococcal infections kill up to 28 children up to the age of 10 after being examined in hospitals every year.
Outside the Czech Republic, mandatory vaccination of children against pneumococcal disease has been introduced in about 40 countries.
Will the vaccination be mandatory?
At the same time, it is said that this vaccination could be mandatory in the future.
As of January, it will be paid by the insurance companies and will be voluntary.
For example, the head of Nahla’s citizens’ association, Rudolf Kalovsky, mentioned that the mandatory vaccination would be better.
His association has been promoting the pneumococcal vaccine for the long term.
The experts at the international conference, in which our association was involved, were not very satisfied with the fact that we have voluntary vaccination.
That's not entirely ideal.
On the other hand, we are glad that we have succeeded in enforcing at least that.
I think that’s the path we have to take now, Kalovsky said.
However, the Ministry of Health does not want to change the vaccination procedure against pneumococcal disease.
At this point, we are not considering this at all, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sesen.
Voluntary vaccination has its drawbacks, the doctors claim.
The chairman of the specialist society of practical pediatricians, Hana Cabrnochova, admits that a voluntary vaccination has its disadvantages.
If all children were vaccinated, then one could think about reducing the number of repeat vaccinations "In a situation where the vaccine is so expensive, we understand the political decision that this vaccination was started as a voluntary," says Cabrnochova.
Experts expect more than 80 percent of parents to vaccinate their infants against pneumococcal disease by next year.
The vaccination against pneumococcal disease is also groundbreaking in that it is paid for as the first area vaccination by health insurance companies and not by the state.
The insurance companies should spend the money on prevention, so they save for further treatment, Cabrnochova explains.
The doctors have to buy the vaccines themselves.
This, however, is a concern of the practical pediatricians, which concerns the purchase of vaccines.
After the initial project, the vaccines should be purchased by the insurance companies and then received by the doctors in the same way as other vaccines issued to them by the state.
Some MPs, however, feared that the insurance companies could "extract the money from health insurance".
That is why doctors will have to buy the vaccines themselves and wait until the insurance companies pay for them.
According to the estimates, the individual practical doctors will have to invest 40,000 crowns per month, which is a significant sum.
This will not be easy, says Cabrnochova.
