A Course Change in Older China
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters that taught them that "Mother Earth is too tired to entertain other children" and "A baby more means a grave more".
They learned these lessons so well that, as government officials in Shanghai, who suddenly began to change course due to the low birth rate and aging population this summer, and encouraged young couples to have more than one child, their answer was immediate and final: “No way.”
We have already invested all our time and energy in a child.
There is nothing left for a second child, said Wang, 31, a staff leader with an 8-month-old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of one-child policy in China, which has spawned two generations of notoriously fat, sluggish single children, affectionately called “little emperors,” a population crisis is brewing in the country.
The average birth rate has fallen to 1.8 children per couple compared to 6 at the time this policy came into force, the UN said.
The Department of Population Affairs is determined, while the number of the population aged 60 years and older in 2020 is expected to increase from 16.7 percent of the population to 31.1 percent explosively by 2050, far above the global average of about 20 percent.
The imbalance is stronger in rich coastal cities with educated populations, such as Shanghai.
Last year, 60-year-olds and older made up almost 22 percent of Shanghai’s reported residents, while the birth rate was below one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, head of Shanghai’s Urban Population and Family Planning Commission, said couples of childbearing age must have babies in order to “help reduce the ratio of aging population shares and alleviate the labor shortage of the future.”
Shanghai will soon be "as old -- but not as rich -- as the developed countries, like Japan and Sweden," she said.
A step-by-step relaxation
Anchored in the country’s 1978 constitution, China’s one-child policy is likely to be the most controversial provision introduced by the ruling Communist Party to date.
Couples who violate this policy must expect enormous fines -- up to three times their annual salary in some regions -- and discrimination in their workplace.
Chinese state representatives have attributed it to this policy that the critical use of natural country resources could be avoided, whereas human rights representatives have condemned abuses in the enforcement of the policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who have already had a child to abort.
Many couples had also had sex-selective abortions, resulting in an unnaturally high ratio of men to women.
In recent years, government representatives for the population have gradually weakened their stance on one-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities and cases in which both husband and wife have been single children -- and in 2007, the tone of many harsh slogans was softened.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at Beijing University’s Institute of Population Research, said government officials have recently even discussed more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children in which a partner is an only child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births.
Posters that taught families to have only one child have been replaced almost overnight by guidelines detailing who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city administration has sent out city employees and volunteers for family planning to visit couples at home and push information sheets under the doors.
She also asked for psychological and financial advice for those who have more than one child.
The response was not encouraging, family planning officials said.
Disappointing reaction
Although officials from a rural small town in the outskirts of Shanghai said there was a surge in requests from couples who want a second child after the campaign started, the urban districts, on the other hand, reported no change.
In the municipality of Huinan with a population of 115,000, as an example, only four to five applications are still submitted per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say the number of births expected in the city for 2010 will still be around 165,000 despite the campaign -- slightly higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee of the Shanghai municipality of Caolu, said financial considerations were probably the main reason why many people no longer want to have children.
They want to give their best to their first, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would like to have two children and this was also legally allowed.
But they own, like many Chinese, only a small amount of government health and life insurance.
Without a social network, they say, this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West mistakenly rate the one-child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is pregnant with her first child in the seventh month.
Yes, we are robbed of the opportunity to have more than one child.
But the problem is not just in politics.
The problem is money.
Other couples give psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the head of staff, said she only wants a child because she was also an only child. "We were the center of the family and used to everyone taking care of us.
We’re not used to taking care of others and we don’t really want to.”
Chen Zijian, a 42-year-old who owns a translation company, said it bluntly.
For middle-class parents with a double career, which lowers the birth rate, he said, it’s about being successful and being selfish.
The age group of today’s 20- to 39-year-olds grew up watching their parents struggle during the early days of the Chinese capitalism experiment and they don’t want such a life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child, he said, places huge demands on the time of the parents.
A mother must give up her social life for at least two years.
Then there is the spatial question -- "You have to rebuild your apartment" -- and the life planning -- "If the child is 9 months old, you must already have a resume ready for the best preschools."
Most of his friends are willing to go through this once, Chen said, but not twice.
Our generation is the first to achieve a higher standard of living, he said.
We don’t want to make too many sacrifices.
