The Cradle of the Dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: The two-meter-long and 1.50-meter-wide animal ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle claws, and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would be nothing special.
But Tawa Hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body features, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday’s journal Science.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in present-day New Mexico, which was then in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangaea on the equator.
Tawa opens a new window on the early evolution of dinosaurs, Nesbitt says.
It shows us a lot about the relationships, the spread and the characteristics of early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in a day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Trias, reports team member Randall Irmis from the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as a new species.
In the course of the excavation, they brought together the remains of a total of five individuals.
Find confirms theories about Dino's early history
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it’s an extraordinary find: “Dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments can be found.”
Other dinosaur experts don’t necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current teaching, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these ancient dinos is most controversial.
For example, experts debate when the lizards split into their three main lines of development: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the tyrannosaurus rex, the velociraptor, and also the birds known as the "long-necked" four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and the feral orniths.
After analyzing Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa Hallae is an original theropod.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, Nesbitt says.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of air sacs, as well as the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the airbags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
At Tawa Hallae, the bones of the spine were also apparently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air sacs, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of giant sauropods later also had air sacs and lightweight bones, probably the common ancestor of both groups had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the lizards first appeared there.
According to this, the three lines of development separated early and spread from South America over all parts of the earth, which at that time as a supercontinent Pang<0xC3><0xA4>a formed a single land mass.
This is due to the fact that the team, together with Tawa Hallae, found the remains of two other, not very closely related theropods.
The three cannot be descended from a common immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says the Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
In his opinion, a distorted picture could result, because in South America only a particularly large number of primitive Dino fossils have been preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to be found.
How the dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare sideline of the reptile tribe to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of the Middle Ages is still puzzling.
During the Triassic, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today's crocodiles and the flight saurian and with numerous other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread throughout the world and developed many new species, while the kinship on the border died out from the Triassic to the Jurassic.
The success story didn’t last forever.
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs accidentally survived, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so that they could beat the competition out of the field.
In any case, the success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite hit a group of animals that had also developed in the Triassic and since then has been tempted by a shadow: the mammals.
