The illusions are a cruel reality
About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in their lives, and in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, sufferers can usually no longer distinguish between the inner and outer worlds, they find themselves in a state of overexcitedness that can lead to hallucinations, size, relationship or persecution.
Voice listening is especially common - voices that command, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also not uncommon.
The affected person can no longer separate the important from the unimportant, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like the dream, psychosis also opens the doors to a flood of ideas and fantasies that come from deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician of the Department of General Psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of the event, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time, he finds himself in a passive role, as in a dream, he is overwhelmed by the events and cannot actively shape them.
Schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
It is usually not possible for them to reconcile reality, the delusions are cruel reality, excluding awakening.
Having experienced a hallucination once in your life
But unlike in the dream, Fuchs says, "the sensual and spatial structure of reality that is perceived in psychosis remains basically preserved."
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are rooted in reality, the alienation of the experience takes place in the real context.
Why exactly our brain beats caprioles, researchers still pose puzzles.
“Exceptions can cause any person to lose their relationship to reality for a short time,” says Fuchs.
But not everyone will develop a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that genes are not the only determining factors.
Researchers assume that there is minimal brain damage in those affected.
We suspect that neuronal maturation of the brain is disturbed at an early stage of development, by a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, for example, explains Fox.
But it remains a mystery how the disruption of the neuronal system occurs, which, moreover, does not manifest itself at all for many years.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be triggers for psychosis if the disposition is present.
Hallucinogenic drugs can also trigger psychoses as they interfere with the transmitter system.
When our brain is hot
