Whether deceptions are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often only a matter of opinion.
Kasten has been collecting reports of hallucinations and delusions for ten years, last year he evaluated his results in the book "The unreal world in our head".
Hallucinations are among the typical side effects of psychosis, but also of many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, these often include diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer’s and brain trauma.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, even the brain hallucinates healthy people.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are composed of memory contents that are usually held back.
They arise when brain areas in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or too little inhibited; when our brain runs hot or even when stimulation is lacking.
Drugs can trigger this condition as well as brain damage or psychosis.
But also arousal, stress, love sadness or other mental states of exception.
In recent studies, up to one-third of respondents reported experiencing hallucinations at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. is 16 years old, living in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attending high school there.
A normal girl, actually.
If there were no pictures and voices.
In the break, it can happen that a sluggish boy with long, dark hair appeals to it.
