They think the shy girl is a daydreamer, but Sarah K. doesn’t dream, she knows that.
She is awake, she hears and sees this boy, just as she hears and sees the girl in the bench next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for moments.
A pleasant feeling is that she likes the boy.
Am I crazy? she sometimes asks herself.
But she knows that this boy and the other delusions are not real and disappear again.
At night, the appearances are usually frightening
Often the deceptions are also a burden.
While sitting in the classroom, she can sometimes not follow the teaching material, because the teacher in her eyes and ears is just introducing a new classmate, while explaining mathematical equations for all the others audible and visible on the board.
At night, the appearances are usually frightening.
When she waits in her dark room for sleep, which comes much too rarely and much too late, she often cannot tell whether she is awake or already dreaming, whether the pictures she sees of the freckles or the girl with the bleeding cut wounds on her arms and legs, appear before her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, she screams at the figures.
Her parents and friends don’t tell her anything about what they would think of her as crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years old.
She graduated last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she made contact on the internet with the psychologist box, she knows exactly that she is not crazy.
Insanity is also a work of art out of desperation
If someone is socially isolated or suffering from irritable bowels, they are more likely to have hallucinations after a while, says Kasten.
I suspect that the brain is then underworked and takes care of its own entertainment.
Sarah K., a single child, as a little girl was afraid of other children, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at the age of 13 that the man she calls Dad has not been her physical father since she can think.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations are active in the same brain regions that also process real impressions and sounds, it is difficult for sufferers like Sarah K. to distinguish between delusions and reality. “Every experience,” says Kasten, “takes place in the brain, the reality is formed there.
Hallucinations are also images that make the brain appear, which is why they seem so real."
Even nocturnal dream images value boxing as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of an acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their delusions as unreal.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to appreciate the hallucinations as a special ability.
Boundary state between dream and hallucination
Unfortunately, in our very consciousness-centered world, imaginary experiences are mostly pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Department of Psychiatry and Psychotherapy at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in D<0xC3><0xBC>sseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful disease, but it also carries positive, creative delusions – it is also a work of art out of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has researched the so-called oneeiroid experience form, a special form of dream-like altered waking consciousness.
Oneiroides are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams, which the experiencer considers real and which he cannot distinguish from the waking state even afterwards.
The oneioid state of consciousness occurs in trauma or disease-related extreme situations, for example in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis with full consciousness.
When a person is threatened with self- and world-loss, for example, by persistent, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own imaginary world decoupled from reality, Schmidt-Degenhard says.
A kind of borderline between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to cope with a situation in reality, a world change takes place, but the real situation is present in the imagination.
An intense form of meaning-making and sensibility in a situation that is inherently intolerable, which allows us humans our own ability to design, not to succumb to a nothingness of the loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in the memory
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his Oneiroid experiences in his book "Herzwechsel" as a rescue of the soul.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness goes on trips for days after heart valve surgery with subsequent heart transplant, while his body is condemned to be motionless on the intensive care unit.
Claussen plunges into a self-created world, visits strange times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden old man, on board a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among nobles who produce drugs from blood.
Taken by a Greek on a motorcycle to his home country, he surfs with his hospital bed in the snow of the Alps and meets a Korean mafioso.
He is fully awake in the imagined event, everything is real, even later in the memory.
These inner journeys differ fundamentally from any dream for Clauses.
Dream is another state, he describes his experience.
In contrast, the memories from mental journeys are still clear to me after years and in extraneous details.
Clearer and more intense even than really experienced.
The intensity of this experience breaks the horizon of our other life-world experiences, says the psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, oneiroids, psychoses, hallucinations, and drug addiction show how fragile our inner images of external reality are also in the wake.
Any change in the state of consciousness, sums up the psychologist box, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be enriching.
