75% of working mothers have problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the result of the study "Fertility and Career of Women in Spain" carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Institute for Women.
The survey of 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working women see their career opportunities limited in the labour market due to their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are major differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children, depending on whether the women work or not and if so, what type of profession they practice.
Those of them who do no other work outside the house, work only half-days or have no fixed employment contract, are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with a permanent job, especially in the public sector, postpone the establishment of a family and motherhood and therefore also have fewer children.
“Women in the 35-49 age group with a permanent job only get their first child on average 3.7 years after contraction, a number that increases to 4.1 years for women with permanent employment who have taken longer to achieve this and who have completed their contraction and the first child much later.
In addition, the type of work also has a major impact on motherhood, albeit less than the calendar in terms of readiness to receive," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account in the age of women in marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, the age at the time of marriage and the first child is the higher the level of education.
This difference was also found in women of the same age.
For example, the women in the group between 35 and 49 years old, depending on whether they only have a primary school diploma or a higher education, were, on average, mothers for the first time with 25.1 or 32.1 in each case.
Furthermore, there is another difference between women, depending on their level of education.
While women with a primary degree get married before their first permanent employment and have their first child, women with a middle or high school degree do just the opposite and first seek a permanent employment and marry after that and then have their first child, Delgado notes.
