Support for braking manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As was the case with the ABS anti-lock braking system back then, and as is the case with the ESP stability control now, the auxiliary braking systems for emergency braking must become mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly approved passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, for the remaining vehicles a grace period was set until the end of February 2011.
The measure adopted by the European Union aims to improve the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help prevent many accidents due to their operation.
The task of the emergency brake assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical brake manoeuvre, which the system detects on the brake pedal based on the brake strength performed by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident before the collision were no longer able to step on the brake pedal and half of them had not braked with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake assist, on the other hand, engages the braking system with maximum force and thereby reduces the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car covers during the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assistant.
There would be even fewer accidents – it is expected that one in four accidents could be prevented with personal injury – as soon as so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects (via radar or a camera) obstacles and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, the system will help increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already unavoidable, the brake assistant applies maximum pressure to the brakes to keep the damage as low as possible.
