New programmes for the assessment of vehicles
In these days of storms and accidents, not only the car repair shops deserve
Every day, thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are towed to workshops where an appraiser must assess the damage and repair costs incurred.
No single accident is the same and calculating the cost of parts and hours of work can be a lengthy and complicated task.
The calculation of the repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros per hand, including the parts and working hours, can take up to two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest computer science tools, it is a matter of minutes
That is why almost 100% of the reviewers use this type of system.
Service and application providers for accident assessment and repair collect the information they receive from manufacturers to process it afterwards and offer it to their customers in the form of a useful program.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American group Solera, is the market leader; 80% of all reviews are produced with their products.
The two other companies competing with in the tool market for review and preparation of a report are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data provided by the manufacturers is anything but easy.
According to Eduardo Vel<0xC3><0xA1>zquez, sales manager of Audatex, 63 manufacturers and importers are working together, each of them providing the information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed is becoming increasingly large, to the point that in the last five years even more versions, variants and motorizations have come to market than in the entire fifteen years before.
As soon as a new car comes on the market, work begins for the companies.
It is a laborious task, because every single one of the thousands of vehicle parts must be catalysed and its price entered.
In addition, each model creates an "intelligent" graphic image on which you can "click" different parts of the vehicle.
If it is a much sold model, the work can be completed in a week if the procedure proceeds quickly.
If it is a less common car, it can already take up to three or four months. Audatex currently has full information on 99.2% of the cars sold in Spain.
Among the more exclusive models, for example, they have information about the Porsche models, but not about Ferrari or Lamborghini.
With regard to the fleet of vehicles driving on the roads, it is over 99%.
Audatex has eight centres worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, the USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) to carry out the documentation work and to produce databases, each of which specialises in specific brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million euros annually in the development of these databases.
Every month, they record 2.5 million data and their customers receive updates every other day.
The development of this enormous flow of information allows companies to use it in different ways and thus offer different products.
The most common use is the use for repairs and repairs, but depending on the country, there are also tools for the management of scrap parts or for calculating the incorrect or residual value of a car.
The only company that informs about a driver about the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer this offer in Spain, but in the United States.
By reviewing the products Audatex offers, you can easily get an overview of the type of support it provides to industry experts.
This company offers ten different tools, where the star of the products is AudaPlus, a standard solution for assessing accidents for the reviewers.
It includes vehicles, motorcycles as well as light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it includes the repair times estimated by the manufacturer or the painting prices.
This tool is paid depending on the purpose of use, i.e. for each opinion.
The most expensive will be for customers who rarely use it, a maximum of ten times a month, namely 5.75 euros per month.
On the other hand, every insurance company that makes thousands of reviews negotiates the price with Audatex.
With other products, such as AudaVIN, it is possible to fully identify a vehicle and the equipment with which it ran from the assembly line using only the chassis number.
AudaGlass deals with the vehicle windows, and AudaSubastas is an internet service that is open to the specialist market and can be used to provide services for vehicles that have been declared to be in total damage.
Your statistics service is very useful in identifying trends, conducting geodemographic analyses or for obtaining information about the deviations by brand and model.
For example, you can examine how many models of a particular car brand had to go into the workshop due to breakdowns or how many of them were involved in a serious accident in a certain period of time.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of computer tools.
It distributes among others Gt Estimate, which is also intended for reviewers and in the same way provides digital images, access to parts or prices and official working hours of the manufacturer.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa Group, which was founded in 1971 as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of damage, breakdowns and maintenance of vehicles.
The GT guide for expert opinions is a reference product on the market.
They work with 24,000 users in workshops, 3,100 reviewers and 53 insurance companies.
Their business volume has increased by 20% annually over the last three years and in 2008 sales amounted to 10.8 million euros.
At the beginning of last year, they also started to go on the international market with the opening of an office in Paris.
Audatex, on the other hand, was founded in 1966 in Germany and established in 1979 in Spain.
According to the company’s sources, 62% of its business is done in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38% in North and South America, working together with 900 insurance companies and 33,000 workshops, 3,000 of them in Spain.
Total worldwide sales of Solera Group (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) amounted to $557 million, 3.35 more than in 2008.
In this country, the company has revenues of 19.1 million euros, 7.2% more than in the previous year.
In 2005, the Solera Group was worth $1 billion on the stock exchange and today its shares are trading at a value of $2.4 billion.
Since 2007, they have been listed on the New York Stock Exchange and part of the Standard & Poor's benchmark index.
